ality of the Landscape: the Coixtlahuaca Valley Archaeology and the Lienzo Seler II -- tMonumentality by numbers -- tTexts in the City: Monumental Inscriptions in Jerusalem's Urban Landscape -- tContributors0 aOpen Accessuhttps://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_abf2funrestricted online access2star  aWhen talking about monuments, size undeniably matters - or does it? But how else can we measure monumentality? Bringing together researchers from various fields such as archaeology, museology, history, sociology, Mesoamerican studies, and art history, this book discusses terminological and methodological approaches in both theoretical contributions and various case studies. While focusing on architectural aspects, this volume also discusses the social meaning of monuments, the role of forced and free labour, as well as textual or inscriptual monumentality. The result is a modern interdisciplinary take on an important concept which is notoriously difficult to define.  afunded by Cluster of Excellence 264 TOPOI  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aHistoric sitesvCongresses. 0aMonumentsxHistoryvCongresses. 0aMonumentsxSocial aspectsvCongresses. 4aAncient History. 4aArchitecture. 4aCultural History. 4aEnergetics. 4aHistory. 4aIdentity. 4aLabour. 4aMonument. 4aPerception. 4aReception. 7aHISTORY / Ancient / General.2bisacsh  aAncient History.  aArchitecture.  aCultural History.  aEnergetics.  aHistory.  aIdentity.  aLabour.  aMonument.  aPerception.  aReception.1 aAutenrieth, Sabrina N., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBernbeck, Reinhard, econtributor.4ct